\ansChap{1}
\ansSec{1.1}
\ansItem{1}{$350$ miles}
\ansExplain{1}{Estimate: $210 \div 6 \approx 35$ mpg, so $35 \times 10 \approx 350$. Exact: $210 \div 6 = 35$ mpg. $35 \times 10 = 350$ miles. Check: estimate matches. \checkmark }
\ansItem{2}{$3\frac {3}{4}$ cups}
\ansExplain{2}{Estimate: $\frac {3}{2}$ cups serves $4$, so $10$ is $2.5$ times as many — about $3.5$--$4$ cups. Exact: $\frac {3}{2} \div 4 = \frac {3}{8}$ per person. $\frac {3}{8} \times 10 = \frac {30}{8} = 3\frac {3}{4}$ cups. Check: $3.75$ is near our estimate. \checkmark }
\ansItem{3}{$64$ km}
\ansExplain{3}{Estimate: $3$ cm is $24$ km, so $1$ cm $\approx 8$ km, and $8$ cm $\approx 64$ km. Exact: $\frac {3}{24} = \frac {8}{d}$, cross-multiply: $3d = 192$, $d = 64$ km. Check: estimate matches exactly. \checkmark }
\ansItem{4}{$30$ min}
\ansExplain{4}{Estimate: $120$ pages in $8$ min is about $15$ per min. $450 \div 15 = 30$ min. Exact: same calculation. Check: $450$ is nearly $4 \times 120$, so time should be nearly $4 \times 8 = 32$ min — $30$ is close. \checkmark }
\ansItem{5}{Large by $\$2$/gal}
\ansExplain{5}{Estimate: Small is about $\$18$ for $\frac {3}{4}$ gal $= \$24$/gal. Large is about $\$33$ for $1.5$ gal $\approx \$22$/gal. Exact: Small: $18 \div 0.75 = \$24$/gal. Large: $33 \div 1.5 = \$22$/gal. Large saves $\$2$ per gallon. \checkmark }
\ansChap{2}
\ansSec{2.1}
\ansItem{1}{$\$7$}
\ansExplain{1}{Convert: $20\% = 0.20$. Multiply: $0.20 \times 35 = \$7$. That's the amount you add for the server.}
\ansItem{2}{$50\%$}
\ansExplain{2}{The markup is $18 - 12 = \$6$. Divide by the original: $6 \div 12 = 0.5$. Multiply by $100$: $0.5 \times 100 = 50\%$.}
\ansItem{3}{$\$50$}
\ansExplain{3}{After $20\%$ off, you pay $80\%$. So $\$40 = 0.80 \times \text {original}$. Divide: $40 \div 0.80 = \$50$.}
\ansItem{4}{$\$270$}
\ansExplain{4}{Tax $= 0.08 \times 250 = \$20$. Total $= 250 + 20 = \$270$.}
\ansItem{5}{$20\%$}
\ansExplain{5}{Food cost $= 42 - 7 = \$35$. Percent $= 7 \div 35 = 0.20 = 20\%$.}
\ansChap{3}
\ansSec{3.1}
\ansItem{1}{$\$80$}
\ansExplain{1}{Use $I = Prt$: $I = 800 \times 0.05 \times 2 = \$80$. This is the money the bank pays you for keeping your savings there.}
\ansItem{2}{$\$288$}
\ansExplain{2}{$I = 1{,}200 \times 0.06 \times 4 = \$288$. This is the extra cost of borrowing the money.}
\ansItem{3}{Account B ($\$50$ vs.\ $\$45$)}
\ansExplain{3}{A: $I = 500 \times 0.03 \times 3 = \$45$. B: $I = 500 \times 0.02 \times 5 = \$50$. Even though B has a lower rate, the longer time makes it earn $\$5$ more.}
\ansItem{4}{$4\%$}
\ansExplain{4}{Solve for $r$: $240 = 2{,}000 \times r \times 3$. So $6{,}000r = 240$ and $r = 0.04 = 4\%$.}
\ansItem{5}{$4$ years}
\ansExplain{5}{Solve for $t$: $150 = 1{,}500 \times 0.025 \times t$. So $37.5t = 150$ and $t = 4$ years.}
\ansChap{4}
\ansSec{4.1}
\ansItem{1}{$8$}
\ansExplain{1}{The opposite of $-8$ is $8$. Both are $8$ units from $0$ on opposite sides of the number line.}
\ansItem{2}{$12$ and $7$}
\ansExplain{2}{Absolute value is distance from $0$. $|-12| = 12$ and $|7| = 7$.}
\ansItem{3}{$<$}
\ansExplain{3}{Convert: $-\frac {2}{3} \approx -0.667$. Since $-0.667$ is farther left than $-0.5$, we have $-\frac {2}{3} < -0.5$.}
\ansItem{4}{$-1, \;-0.75, \;-\frac {1}{4}, \;0.3, \;\frac {1}{2}$}
\ansExplain{4}{Convert all to decimals: $0.5, -0.75, -0.25, 0.3, -1$. Order from most negative to most positive: $-1 < -0.75 < -0.25 < 0.3 < 0.5$.}
\ansItem{5}{True}
\ansChap{5}
\ansSec{5.1}
\ansItem{1}{$\$937.88$}
\ansExplain{1}{Total catch: $345.5 + 278.75 = 624.25$ lb. Sold: $624.25 \times \frac {1}{3} = 208.08\overline {3}$ lb. Revenue: $208.08\overline {3} \times 4.50 \approx \$937.88$.}
\ansItem{2}{$-11.25°$F}
\ansExplain{2}{Start: $-18$. Drop: $-18 + (-5.5) = -23.5$. Rise: $-23.5 + 12.25 = -11.25°$F.}
\ansItem{3}{$3{,}755$ ft}
\ansExplain{3}{After descent: $4{,}380 - 1{,}250 = 3{,}130$ ft. Climbs back $\frac {1}{2} \times 1{,}250 = 625$ ft. Final: $3{,}130 + 625 = 3{,}755$ ft.}
\ansItem{4}{$\$240$}
\ansExplain{4}{Housing: $\frac {2}{5} \times 1{,}200 = \$480$. Food: $\frac {1}{4} \times 1{,}200 = \$300$. Spent: $480 + 300 + 180 = \$960$. Left: $1{,}200 - 960 = \$240$.}
\ansItem{5}{$-5\frac {1}{2}$}
\ansExplain{5}{Multiply first: $-\frac {1}{2} \times 8 = -4$. Divide: $\frac {3}{4} \div (-\frac {1}{2}) = \frac {3}{4} \times (-2) = -\frac {3}{2}$. Add: $-4 + (-\frac {3}{2}) = -\frac {11}{2} = -5\frac {1}{2}$.}
\ansChap{6}
\ansSec{6.1}
\ansItem{1}{No}
\ansExplain{1}{Check: $4 + 6 = 10$, but $10 < 11$. The two shorter sides cannot reach each other. The triangle inequality fails, so no triangle is possible.}
\ansItem{2}{Draw $5$ cm base; arc $5$ cm from each endpoint; connect intersection}
\ansExplain{2}{Step 1: Draw a $5$ cm segment (one side). Step 2: Arc $5$ cm from the left endpoint (all points at distance $5$). Step 3: Arc $5$ cm from the right endpoint. Step 4: Connect the intersection — it is $5$ cm from both endpoints, making all sides equal.}
\ansItem{3}{Many}
\ansExplain{3}{The sides must add to $10$ (half the perimeter). Possible pairs: $1 \times 9$, $2 \times 8$, $3 \times 7$, etc. Perimeter alone does not fix the shape.}
\ansItem{4}{Exactly one}
\ansExplain{4}{Two sides and the included angle (SAS condition) fully determine a triangle. There is only one right triangle with legs $6$ and $8$ cm.}
\ansItem{5}{False}
\ansChap{7}
\ansSec{7.1}
\ansItem{1}{$55°$}
\ansExplain{1}{Complementary angles sum to $90°$. Subtract: $90° - 35° = 55°$.}
\ansItem{2}{$111°$ and $69°$}
\ansExplain{2}{Sum to $180°$: $3x + 15 + 2x + 5 = 180$. Combine: $5x + 20 = 180$. Solve: $5x = 160$, $x = 32$. Angles: $3(32) + 15 = 111°$ and $2(32) + 5 = 69°$. Check: $111 + 69 = 180°$ \checkmark .}
\ansItem{3}{$x = 10$; angles are $45°$}
\ansExplain{3}{Vertical angles are equal: $4x + 5 = 6x - 15$. Subtract $4x$: $5 = 2x - 15$. Add $15$: $20 = 2x$. So $x = 10$. Angle: $4(10) + 5 = 45°$.}
\ansItem{4}{$x = 40$}
\ansExplain{4}{Angles on a line sum to $180°$: $(x + 20) + 2x + 40 = 180$. Combine: $3x + 60 = 180$. Solve: $3x = 120$, $x = 40$. Check: $60 + 80 + 40 = 180°$ \checkmark .}
\ansItem{5}{$17.5°$ and $72.5°$}
\ansExplain{5}{Let the complement be $x$. The angle is $3x + 20$. Sum: $x + 3x + 20 = 90$. Combine: $4x = 70$, $x = 17.5°$. The angle: $3(17.5) + 20 = 72.5°$. Check: $17.5 + 72.5 = 90°$ \checkmark .}
\ansChap{8}
\ansSec{8.1}
\ansItem{1}{No — it is biased}
\ansExplain{1}{Students who arrive early may have different homework habits than others. A better method is to randomly select $10$ names from the class list.}
\ansItem{2}{Population: $5{,}000$ bulbs; sample: $50$ bulbs}
\ansExplain{2}{The factory uses the sample to estimate the quality of the whole batch without testing every single bulb.}
\ansItem{3}{Question, population, method, collect, analyze}
\ansExplain{3}{1) Question: Which lunch is most popular? 2) Population: all students. 3) Method: randomly select $50$ students. 4) Collect: survey their lunch choice. 5) Analyze: tally results and find the most common choice.}
\ansItem{4}{It avoids bias}
\ansExplain{4}{Random sampling gives every member an equal chance of being selected, so the sample is more likely to represent the whole population accurately.}
\ansItem{5}{Biased sample}
\ansExplain{5}{Employees may have opinions influenced by loyalty or job concerns. The population of interest is all potential customers, not just employees.}
\ansChap{9}
\ansSec{9.1}
\ansItem{1}{Team Y averages higher but is more spread out}
\ansExplain{1}{Team Y's higher mean shows better scoring on average, but its larger range means more inconsistency game to game.}
\ansItem{2}{When data sets are large}
\ansExplain{2}{Box plots summarize key statistics (median, quartiles, range) without showing every point, making them easier to read when there are many data values.}
\ansItem{3}{Class A devotes a larger share to sports}
\ansExplain{3}{Circle graphs compare proportions. A larger sector means a bigger fraction of the whole. Class A spends more of their free time on sports.}
\ansItem{4}{Not necessarily}
\ansExplain{4}{Overlap means some members are similar, but the centers may still differ. Compare medians and IQRs to see if the difference is meaningful.}
\ansItem{5}{Categorical data (e.g., favorite color)}
\ansExplain{5}{Histograms need numerical intervals. For categories like favorite color, a frequency table counts each category directly.}
\ansChap{10}
\ansSec{10.1}
\ansItem{1}{Group A}
\ansExplain{1}{Group A has a smaller range ($20$ vs.\ $40$) and smaller IQR ($8$ vs.\ $18$), meaning its data is more tightly clustered around the center.}
\ansItem{2}{Y averages slightly more but is much less consistent}
\ansExplain{2}{Student Y's IQR is nearly triple Student X's, meaning Y's daily steps vary much more. X is more consistent day to day.}
\ansItem{3}{IQR ignores outliers}
\ansExplain{3}{Range uses only the two extreme values, which can be misleading if there is an outlier. IQR measures the spread of the middle $50\%$ and gives a more stable comparison.}
\ansItem{4}{Range $= 45$; IQR $= 10$; IQR is better}
\ansExplain{4}{Range: $50 - 5 = 45$. $Q_1 = 8$, $Q_3 = 18$, so IQR $= 10$. The outlier $50$ inflates the range. IQR shows the typical spread more accurately.}
\ansItem{5}{Class A}
\ansExplain{5}{Class A has a higher median ($82$ vs.\ $78$) and a smaller IQR ($6$ vs.\ $14$), meaning most students scored close to $82$. Class B is both lower and more spread out.}
\ansChap{11}
\ansSec{11.1}
\ansItem{1}{$0.48$; close to the theoretical $0.50$}
\ansExplain{1}{$P = 48 \div 100 = 0.48$. The theoretical probability is $0.50$. The small difference is expected — with more tosses, the experimental value would get closer to $0.50$.}
\ansItem{2}{$0.30$; slightly above $0.25$ but likely fair}
\ansExplain{2}{$P = 24 \div 80 = 0.30$. Theoretical $= 0.25$. The small difference could be due to chance in $80$ trials. More spins would help confirm.}
\ansItem{3}{Use a coin; H = boy, T = girl; flip $3$ times per trial}
\ansExplain{3}{Each child is equally likely to be a boy or girl — like a coin flip. Flip $3$ coins per trial. Record how many trials give $3$ tails (all girls). Repeat $50$+ trials. Divide all-girl trials by total trials.}
\ansItem{4}{$0.25$; theoretical is $\frac {1}{6} \approx 0.167$}
\ansExplain{4}{$P = 15 \div 60 = 0.25$. Theoretical $= \frac {1}{6} \approx 0.167$. The experimental value is noticeably higher — this could be chance, or the die may not be fair.}
\ansItem{5}{Rain = digits $0$--$3$; experimental $P = 0.40$}
\ansExplain{5}{$40\% = 4$ out of $10$ digits. Choose $0, 1, 2, 3$ for rain. In the $10$ trials: rain digits are $3, 1, 0, 2$ — that's $4$ rain events. $P = 4 \div 10 = 0.40$.}
